id="post-4342" class="post-4342 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-music-art tag-revelstoke"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/03/28/band-of-the-month-revelstoke/" title="Permalink to Band of the Month: Revelstoke" rel="bookmark">Band of the Month: Revelstoke</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2014/03/28 8:30 am"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/03/28/band-of-the-month-revelstoke/" title="Band of the Month: Revelstoke" rel="bookmark">2014/03/28 8:30 am</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="comments-link"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/03/28/band-of-the-month-revelstoke/#comments">Leave a Comment</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/greg/" title="by Greg" rel="author">Greg</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>Happy Spring! We made it!!</p><p>Today&#8217;s band is <a
href="http://revelstoke.bandcamp.com/ ">Revelstoke</a>.</p><p><a
href="http://revelstoke.bandcamp.com/ ">Revelstoke</a>, inspired by a sleepy town nestled in the foothills of the Rocky&#8217;s, and propelled by the influence of the Toronto urban soundscape. His first ep, &#8216;My oh My&#8217; is a gentle journey through memorable vocal refrains, guitar looping, and occasionally accented by frantic and unconventional banjo layering. Revelstoke depicts the wonderfully patient and beautifully brooding marriage between the calm and the chaotic.</p><p>Check it out!</p><p><iframe
style="border: 0; width: 100%; height: 120px;" src="http://bandcamp.com/EmbeddedPlayer/album=3619099756/size=large/bgcol=ffffff/linkcol=0687f5/tracklist=false/artwork=small/transparent=true/" seamless><a
href="http://revelstoke.bandcamp.com/album/my-oh-my">My-Oh-My by Revelstoke</a></iframe></p><p>Band of the Month by Greg O&#8217;Toole</p><div
